result.execSummary:
The defendant Barbara E Chambers was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manuf/Deliver Amphetamine(<=3g), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(e)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

3:55 pm Def in court w/Atty Brian K. Barton.  Emily E. Hynek appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

14CF-480   Count 2 - Delivery of Methamphetamine (Fel)  GUILTY.       Counts 1 & 3 - Dismissed but read-in
COURT is satisfied that the plea is F, I & V made.  Sufficient factual basis.  Found guilty and convicted.
Hynek asks for probation.  Three years is necessary....  Not sure that confinement is necessary.  Barton concurs with Ms. Hynek for the most part.  Ms. Chambers finds herself here today for a number of reasons.  She takes total responsibility...   She still graduated HS.  She's homelss...  She's attempted to contact the trustee of her mother's estate.  She's was asking for a place to live but they are not doing it. If she doesn't get the structure now, she'll falter sooner than laters.  DOC can probice her structure but asks that she not have further penalty...  
COURT calls Atty. Sayner-GAL for Bart in the estate case.  Asks why he and the estate are not providing any support for Barb.  Sayner was going to set up an appointment with her.  There's a trustee and a PR.  COURT asks that he contact them and get them to set up a place for her to live ASAP.  Ms. Chambers to go see Atty. Sayner tomorrow at 1 pm.  COURT:  If Barb doesn't have a place to live w/in 30 days, this will be for formal probate and I will hear it.  COURT addresses Barbara further.
